passages.text: Accelink 002281.SZ 002281 CH

Accelink reported 1H25 results on 27 August after market close, with revenue up by \(68.6\%\) y- y, translating to \(66.1\%\) y- y growth in 2Q25 (+35.9% q- q). The 2Q25 revenue growth beat our estimates by \(24\%\) , likely driven by stronger momentum in data center transceivers, in our view. Earnings grew \(78.4\%\) y- y in 1H25 (2Q25: \(69.3\%\) y- y), in line with our estimates. GPM declined 2.2pp y- y in 2Q25, mainly driven by product mix change (more contributions from optical transceivers), but partially offset by its effective expense control (opex down by 0.3pp y- y in 1H25). We raise FY25- 27F revenue forecasts by \(5 - 21\%\) and earnings forecasts by \(4 - 19\%\) to reflect better DC transceiver demand. We maintain our Buy rating and raise TP to CNY80, based on 43x FY26F EPS of CNY1.87 (previously 36x), in line with a FY24- 27F earnings CAGR of \(43\%\) . The stock is trading at 36.7x FY26F EPS.

China CSPs capex might still rise despite uncertainty over advanced AI chip export control As one of the key suppliers of high- end optical transceivers for China Cloud service providers (CSPs), we think Accelink is well positioned to benefit from likely capex increase for CSPs in 2H25F and 2026F. Despite the recent turmoil about NVIDIA's (NVDA US, Not rated) H20 chip exports, we think there are still solid demand for advanced AI chips from the US and China's leading AI chipmakers. Moreover, we think Huawei's (unlisted) Cloud Matrix 384 super node (see our AI thematic report: Huawei Cloud Matrix 384) which is equipped with Huawei's Ascend AI chips might gain traction in China's CSP market, and Accelink will be a key beneficiary as a long- time partner of Huawei. We estimate Accelink will deliver a \(53\%\) revenue CAGR in FY24- 27F for optical transceivers, which should contribute \(49\%\) of revenue in FY27F.

In- house designed optical chips play more crucial roles in China's AI ecosystem autonomy Accelink is one of the few players in China's optical communication market capable of designing and producing optical chips (EML, Vcsel, CW laser) in- house. The company is able to use in- house designed optical chips for its transceiver products in the mid- to- low end segment (400G and below); while it is striving to tap into high- end chip segment. Geopolitical risk and China's resolution on tech / AI ecosystem autonomy underscore the importance of domestic optical chips; and we believe the company could enjoy sustainable demand from 1.6T / 3.2T transceivers and CPO switches.
Source: Company data, Nomura estimates

Accelink Technologies is a China- based company, principally engaged in the development and production of optical components and subsystem products. The company mainly provides optical components and modules which are mainly applied in the optical fiber access and transmission.
Our TP of CNY80.00 is based on 43x 2026F EPS of CNY1.67 in line with FY25- 27F earnings CAGR of 43%. The benchmark index is CSI 300 index.

Downside risks include: (1) lower- than- expected demand for optical components and modules from the datacom and telecom market; (2) slower- than- expected R&D progress on optical chipsets; (3) worse- than- expected pricing competition and margin dilution; and (4) worse- than- expected sanctions in technology sector.

Accelink is a leading optical component producer, with social responsibility to offer infrastructure products for telecom networks and data centers. The telecom equipment manufacturing requires land, equipment and other materials which may have impacts to the environment, while factory automation may help to reduce such impacts. Corporate governance needs improvement in terms of shareholder return, etc.

1H25 and 2Q25 earnings reviewAccelink recorded revenue growth of \(68.6\%\) y- y in 1H25, translating to \(66.1\%\) y- y growth in 2Q25 (+35.9% q- q). The 2Q25 revenue growth beat our estimates by \(24\%\) , likely driven by stronger momentum in data center transceivers, in our view. Earnings grew \(78.4\%\) y- y in 1H25 (2Q25: \(69.3\%\) y- y), in line with our estimates. GPM declined 2.2pp y- y in 2Q25, mainly due to product mix change (more contributions from optical transceivers), but partially offset by effective expenses control with opex down by 0.3pp y- y in 1H25.
Fig.1:Accelink-1H25&2Q25earningsreview
Source: Company data, Nomura research

Earnings forecast revisionsWe raise FY25- 27F revenues by \(5 - 21\%\) to reflect the better momentum from transceiver products, and slightly lower FY25- 27F GPM by \(0.1 - 0.2pp\) to reflect a higher contribution from optical transceivers amid lower margins and inefficiency of the new production base in the early stage. As a result, our FY25- 27F earnings increase by \(4 - 19\%\) .
Fig.2:Accelink-earnings forecast revisions
Source: Company data, Nomura estimates

We raise FY25- 27F Access & Data segment revenue by \(6 - 26\%\) to reflect stronger data center transceiver demand, driven by increased AI investment in China. We also raise FY25- 27F revenue for the China market by \(6 - 11\%\) , and raise that for the overseas market by \(1 - 58\%\) to reflect overseas market expansion.
Fig.3:Accelink-earnings forecast summary by segment
Source: Company data, Nomura estimates

Our FY25- 27F revenue forecasts are \(5 - 23\%\) above WIND consensus estimates, as we have a more positive outlook on demand growth from the data center market in the next two years. Our FY25F earnings are \(3\%\) lower than consensus and FY26- 27F earnings are \(2 - 9\%\) higher, as we are more cautious on the company's margin expansion in the short term.
Fig.4:Accelink-Nomura vs consensus
Source: Company data, WIND, Nomura estimates
We raise our TP to CNY80, based on 43x (previously 36x) FY26F EPS of CNY1.87, in line with a FY24- 27F earnings CAGR of \(43\%\) .

Downside risks include: (1) lower- than- expected demand for optical components and modules from the datacom and telecom market; (2) slower- than- expected R&D progress on optical chipsets; (3) worse- than- expected pricing competition and margin dilution; and (4) potential escalation of geopolitical risks.
